Date parsing from free-form strings is trickier than it looks, so here's a function with explicit handling for your three formats rather than relying on `new Date()` which has inconsistent behavior across browsers and locales:

```js
function parseUserDate(input) {
  const trimmed = input.trim();

  // Format: YYYY-MM-DD (ISO)
  const isoMatch = trimmed.match(/^(\d{4})-(\d{2})-(\d{2})$/);
  if (isoMatch) return new Date(isoMatch[1], isoMatch[2] - 1, isoMatch[3]);

  // Format: MM/DD/YYYY
  const slashMatch = trimmed.match(/^(\d{1,2})\/(\d{1,2})\/(\d{4})$/);
  if (slashMatch) return new Date(slashMatch[3], slashMatch[1] - 1, slashMatch[2]);

  // Format: Month DD, YYYY
  const longMatch = trimmed.match(/^([A-Za-z]+)\s+(\d{1,2}),?\s+(\d{4})$/);
  if (longMatch) {
    const testDate = new Date(`${longMatch[1]} ${longMatch[2]}, ${longMatch[3]}`);
    if (!isNaN(testDate)) return testDate;
  }

  return null;
}
```

A few caveats: this doesn't validate logical dates (e.g., February 30), and users might type formats you haven't anticipated. You might want to show a preview of the parsed date back to the user so they can confirm it was interpreted correctly. For production use, a library like date-fns would handle edge cases more robustly, but for a personal project this explicit approach should serve you well.

